### Register Service with Container Injection in Laravel

Source: https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/octane

Demonstrates a service provider registration that injects the entire application service container into a singleton service. This pattern can cause issues in Octane because the injected container instance becomes stale on subsequent requests as the same application instance is reused.

```php
use App\Service;
use Illuminate\Contracts\Foundation\Application;

/**
 * Register any application services.
 */
public function register(): void
{
    $this->app->singleton(Service::class, function (Application $app) {
        return new Service($app);
    });
}
```

--------------------------------

### Inject Service Container Dependencies into Components

Source: https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/blade

Laravel's service container can automatically inject dependencies into the component constructor. List these dependencies before any data attributes passed to the component.

```php
use App\Services\AlertCreator;

/**
 * Create the component instance.
 */
public function __construct(
    public AlertCreator $creator,
    public string $type,
    public string $message,
) {}
```

--------------------------------

### Inject Form Request into Controller Method

Source: https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/validation

Demonstrates how to type-hint a custom Form Request in a controller method. Laravel automatically validates the request before the method is executed, allowing access to validated data via the validated or safe methods.

```php
/**
 * Store a new blog post.
 */
public function store(StorePostRequest $request): RedirectResponse
{
    // The incoming request is valid...

    // Retrieve the validated input data...
    $validated = $request->validated();

    // Retrieve a portion of the validated input data...
    $validated = $request->safe()->only(['name', 'email']);
    $validated = $request->safe()->except(['name', 'email']);

    // Store the blog post...

    return redirect('/posts');
}
```

### Service Providers > Introduction

Source: https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/providers

Service providers are the central place of all Laravel application bootstrapping. Your own application, as well as all of Laravel's core services, are bootstrapped via service providers. In general, bootstrapping means **registering** things, including registering service container bindings, event listeners, middleware, and even routes. Service providers are the central place to configure your application. Laravel uses dozens of service providers internally to bootstrap its core services, such as the mailer, queue, cache, and others. Many of these providers are "deferred" providers, meaning they will not be loaded on every request, but only when the services they provide are actually needed.

--------------------------------

### Request Lifecycle > Lifecycle Overview > Service Providers

Source: https://laravel.com/docs/12.x/lifecycle

One of the most important kernel bootstrapping actions is loading the [service providers](/docs/12.x/providers) for your application. Service providers are responsible for bootstrapping all of the framework's various components, such as the database, queue, validation, and routing components. Laravel will iterate through this list of providers and instantiate each of them. After instantiating the providers, the `register` method will be called on all of the providers. Then, once all of the providers have been registered, the `boot` method will be called on each provider. This is so service providers may depend on every container binding being registered and available by the time their `boot` method is executed. Essentially every major feature offered by Laravel is bootstrapped and configured by a service provider. Since they bootstrap and configure so many features offered by the framework, service providers are the most important aspect of the entire Laravel bootstrap process. While the framework internally uses dozens of service providers, you also have the option to create your own. You can find a list of the user-defined or third-party service providers that your application is using in the `bootstrap/providers.php` file.

### Livewire: Enable Live Updates with .live Modifier

Source: https://livewire.laravel.com/docs/4.x/forms

This snippet demonstrates how to use the `.live` modifier on `wire:model` to synchronize form input fields with backend properties in real-time as the user types. It's useful for features like live search.

```blade
<input type="text" wire:model.live="title">
```

--------------------------------

### Targeting Property Updates with wire:loading

Source: https://livewire.laravel.com/docs/4.x/wire-loading

This example illustrates how to target specific component property updates with `wire:target`. The loading indicator will display when the specified property (e.g., 'username') is updated via `wire:model.live`, providing feedback during real-time validation or updates.

```blade
<form wire:submit="save">
    <input type="text" wire:model.live="username">
    @error('username') <span>{{ $message }}</span> @enderror

    <div wire:loading wire:target="username">
        Checking availability of username...
    </div>

    <!-- ... -->
</form>
```

--------------------------------

### Livewire Basic Polling with wire:poll

Source: https://livewire.laravel.com/docs/4.x/wire-poll

Demonstrates the basic usage of the wire:poll directive in a Livewire Blade template. This will cause the component to re-render and update its content at a default interval (2.5 seconds).

```blade
<div wire:poll>
    Subscribers: {{ $count }}
</div>
```

--------------------------------

### Dispatch Livewire Events from Alpine.js

Source: https://livewire.laravel.com/docs/4.x/events

This code snippet illustrates dispatching Livewire events from Alpine.js. It shows a basic dispatch using `$dispatch('event-name')` and how to include additional data with the event by passing a second argument.

```html
<button x-on:click="$dispatch('post-created')">...</button>
```

```html
<button x-on:click="$dispatch('post-created', { title: 'Post Title' })">...</button>
```

--------------------------------

### Real-time Validation with #[Validate] in Livewire

Source: https://livewire.laravel.com/docs/4.x/forms

Shows how to enable real-time validation for specific fields in Livewire by using the `#[Validate]` attribute without any rules. This triggers validation on property updates, for example, when using `wire:model.live.blur`.

```php
<?php

namespace App\Livewire\Forms;

use Livewire\Attributes\Validate;
use Illuminate\Validation\Rule;
use App\Models\Post;
use Livewire\Form;

class PostForm extends Form
{
    public ?Post $post;

    #[Validate] // Enables real-time validation for title
    public $title = '';

    public $content = '';

    protected function rules()
    {
        return [
            'title' => [
                'required',
                Rule::unique('posts')->ignore($this->post),
            ],
            'content' => 'required|min:5',
        ];
    }

    // ...

    public function update()
    {
        $this->validate();

        $this->post->update($this->only(['title', 'content']));

        $this->reset();
    }
}

```

### Access Theme Design Tokens as CSS Variables (CSS)

Source: https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com/blob/main/src/blog/tailwindcss-v4/index.mdx

This generated CSS demonstrates how Tailwind CSS v4.0 automatically converts `@theme` configurations into standard CSS custom properties (variables) within the `:root` selector. This makes all design tokens readily available for runtime use, enabling dynamic styling and integration with JavaScript animation libraries.

```css
:root {
  --font-display: "Satoshi", "sans-serif";

  --breakpoint-3xl: 1920px;

  --color-avocado-100: oklch(0.99 0 0);
  --color-avocado-200: oklch(0.98 0.04 113.22);
  --color-avocado-300: oklch(0.94 0.11 115.03);
  --color-avocado-400: oklch(0.92 0.19 114.08);
  --color-avocado-500: oklch(0.84 0.18 117.33);
  --color-avocado-600: oklch(0.53 0.12 118.34);

  --ease-fluid: cubic-bezier(0.3, 0, 0, 1);
  --ease-snappy: cubic-bezier(0.2, 0, 0, 1);

  /* ... */
}
```

--------------------------------

### Customize Tailwind Theme with CSS @theme Directive

Source: https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com/blob/main/src/docs/adding-custom-styles.mdx

To modify Tailwind's default design tokens such as color palette, spacing, typography, or breakpoints, define your customizations using the `@theme` directive within your CSS. This allows for global adjustments to the framework's design system, ensuring consistency across your project.

```css
/* [!code filename:CSS] */
@theme {
  --font-display: "Satoshi", "sans-serif";

  --breakpoint-3xl: 120rem;

  --color-avocado-100: oklch(0.99 0 0);
  --color-avocado-200: oklch(0.98 0.04 113.22);
  --color-avocado-300: oklch(0.94 0.11 115.03);
  --color-avocado-400: oklch(0.92 0.19 114.08);
  --color-avocado-500: oklch(0.84 0.18 117.33);
  --color-avocado-600: oklch(0.53 0.12 118.34);

  --ease-fluid: cubic-bezier(0.3, 0, 0, 1);
  --ease-snappy: cubic-bezier(0.2, 0, 0, 1);

  /* ... */
}
```

--------------------------------

### Responsive Breakpoints in Tailwind CSS

Source: https://context7.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com/llms.txt

Illustrates mobile-first responsive design using Tailwind's default breakpoints (sm: 40rem, md: 48rem, lg: 64rem, xl: 80rem, 2xl: 96rem). Shows responsive grid layouts, text sizing, and spacing that adapt across different screen sizes.

```html
<!-- Mobile-first responsive design -->
<div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-4">
  <div>Responsive grid item</div>
</div>

<!-- Responsive text sizing -->
<h1 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
  Responsive heading
</h1>

<!-- Responsive spacing -->
<div class="p-4 sm:p-6 md:p-8 lg:p-12">
  Responsive padding
</div>
```

--------------------------------

### Apply Custom Tailwind CSS Breakpoints in HTML

Source: https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com/blob/main/src/docs/responsive-design.mdx

This HTML snippet illustrates how to utilize custom breakpoints defined in your Tailwind CSS theme. Once breakpoints like `xs` and `3xl` are configured, you can apply responsive utility classes by prefixing them with the custom breakpoint name, such as `xs:grid-cols-2` or `3xl:grid-cols-6`, to control layout changes at specific screen sizes.

```html
<div class="grid xs:grid-cols-2 3xl:grid-cols-6">
  <!-- ... -->
</div>
```

### Introduction

Source: https://context7.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss.com/llms.txt

The core philosophy of Tailwind CSS v4 revolves around design tokens called theme variables, which define your project's colors, typography, spacing, shadows, and other design decisions. These theme variables automatically generate corresponding utility classes, creating a seamless connection between your design system and the classes available in your HTML. The framework includes a comprehensive variant system for handling states (hover, focus), responsive breakpoints, dark mode, and many other conditions, all prefixed to utility classes like `hover:bg-blue-500` or `md:flex`.

